Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in the dataset are:

  • The duration of the bike ride.
  • Types of users.
  • Age of the member.
  • Gender of the member.

Data cleaning

In [112]:
# add column to store the ride duration by hour
df['duration_hour'] = df['duration_sec']/3600
In [113]:
# add column for user age based on current year 
import datetime
current_year = datetime.datetime.now().year
df['member_age'] = current_year - df['member_birth_year']

#set missing values of 'member_age' to median
age_median = df['member_age'].median()
df['member_age'] = df['member_age'].fillna(age_median)
df['member_age'] = df['member_age'].astype('int64')

df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])
# Start time weekday
df['start_time_weekday'] = df['start_time'].dt.strftime('%a')
df['hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour
In [114]:
# fille na gender with other
df['member_gender'] = df['member_gender'].fillna('Other')

#common functions

def chart_labels(title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

Older member tend to take shorter trip.

2. Relationships between user type and age

In [125]:
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='user_type', y='member_age');
chart_labels('Relationships between user type and age','Age','User Type')
In [126]:
# Utilize a violin chart for better clarity.
sns.violinplot(data=df, x='user_type', y='member_age');
chart_labels('Relationships between user type and age','Age','User Type')

The age distribution for "Customer" users has a higher concentration of users in the age range of 20 to 40 compared to "Subscriber" users.

3. The relationship between User Type and Gender

In [127]:
df_pivoted = df.pivot_table('duration_hour', 'member_gender', 'user_type', aggfunc="count")

sns.heatmap(data=df_pivoted, annot=True, fmt=".0f", cmap='vlag')
chart_labels('The relationship between User Type and Gender','User Type','Gender')

A significant number of male subscribers exist.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Older member tend to take shorter trip.
  • The age distribution for "Customer" users has a higher concentration of users in the age range of 20 to 40 compared to "Subscriber" users
  • A significant number of male subscribers exist.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Most users belong to the 'Subscriber' user type. However, it's worth noting that among 'Customer' users, a significant portion falls within the age range of 20-40 years old, and they tend to take longer trips.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Create plots of three or more variables to investigate your data even further. Make sure that your investigations are justified, and follow from your work in the previous sections.

1. Daily Usage Per User Type and Gender

In [128]:
# Daily usage - user type and gender
chart = sns.catplot(data=df, x='start_time_weekday', col='user_type', hue='member_gender', kind='count', sharey = False, height=5, aspect=2);
chart._legend.set_title('Gender')
chart.set_axis_labels('Day', 'Number of Bike Trips')
chart.fig.suptitle('Daily Usage Per User Type and Gender',fontsize=16)
Out[128]:
Text(0.5, 0.98, 'Daily Usage Per User Type and Gender')

The number of subscriber users is more than customer users. The number of records on Thursday is higher for both types compared to other days.

2. User Type, Gender and Age

In [129]:
sns.violinplot(data=df, x='member_gender', y='member_age', hue="user_type", split=True,  inner="quartile")
chart_labels('User Type, Gender and Age','Gender','Age')

It appears that both customers and subscribers share the same age range for both males and females.

3. Duration Every Weekday Based on User Type

In [130]:
weekdays = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']
sns.pointplot(data=df, x='start_time_weekday', y='duration_hour', hue='user_type',order=weekdays,
              palette = 'Blues', linestyles='', dodge=0.4)
plt.legend(title='User Type');
chart_labels('Duration Every Weekday Based on User Type','Weekdays','Duration')

Customer users tend to take longer trips than Subscriber users. Users tend to take longer trips on Saturdays and Sundays.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • The number of subscriber users is more than customer users. The number of records on Thursday is higher for both types compared to other days.
  • Customer users tend to take longer trips than Subscriber users. Users tend to take longer trips on Saturdays and Sundays.

Conclusions¶

  • Older member tend to take shorter trip.
  • The age distribution for "Customer" users has a higher concentration of users in the age range of 20 to 40 compared to "Subscriber" users
  • A significant number of male subscribers exist.
  • Customer users tend to take longer trips than Subscriber users. Users tend to take longer trips on Saturdays and Sundays.
